    <section id="fluids" class="content-section">
      <h2>Sub-Cutaneous Fluids</h2>
      <p>Sub-Q fluids — given under the skin and absorbed into the body — are one of the most effective tools for managing CKD. They compensate for the kidneys' inability to concentrate urine, reduce the buildup of toxins, and often produce a dramatic improvement in how a cat feels within hours of administration.</p>
      <p>Many owners give sub-Q fluids at home. It sounds daunting. It becomes routine within a few sessions, and the difference it makes is usually visible the same day.</p>

      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>If your vet hasn't raised this,</strong> ask directly: "Is my cat a candidate for home sub-Q fluids?" If they say no without a clear reason, ask why. For most CKD cats from Stage 2 onward, it's at least worth discussing.
      </div>

      <h3>What you need</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Lactated Ringer's solution or 0.9% saline (your vet prescribes this)</li>
        <li>IV administration set / drip line</li>
        <li>Needles — typically 18 or 20 gauge (your vet will advise)</li>
        <li>A warm, calm space and a second pair of hands helps at first</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>How much and how often</h3>
      <p>Frequency and volume depend on your cat's stage, symptoms, and how well they're maintaining hydration through drinking. Your vet should give you a starting dose — commonly 100–150ml every 2–3 days for moderate CKD, though this varies significantly. Watch for fluid retention (puffiness under the skin) as a sign you may be giving too much too fast.</p>

      <div class="content-callout content-callout--amber">
        <strong>US and Canada note:</strong> In the US and Canada, sub-Q fluids for home administration typically require a vet prescription. Some vets are hesitant to train owners — if yours is reluctant, it is reasonable to ask why, and to seek a second opinion. Many feline specialists consider home fluids standard of care for moderate-to-advanced CKD.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="nausea" class="content-section">
      <h2>Anti-Nausea Medication — Often the Most Urgent Intervention</h2>
      <p>Uraemia — the buildup of waste products the kidneys can't filter — causes chronic nausea. This is the most common reason CKD cats stop eating. It is also frequently under-treated.</p>
      <p>If your cat has stopped eating and anti-nausea medication hasn't been discussed, that is the first question to ask.</p>

      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Maropitant (Cerenia)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">The most commonly used anti-nausea medication in cats. Available as an injection or tablet. Often produces visible improvement in appetite within 24 hours. Ask for this by name if it hasn't been offered.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Ondansetron</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Another anti-nausea option, sometimes used when maropitant isn't effective or tolerated. Available in tablet form and compounded versions.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Famotidine (Pepcid)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Reduces stomach acid, which can contribute to nausea in CKD cats. Often used alongside maropitant. Available over the counter in the US and Canada — but confirm dosing with your vet before using.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="appetite" class="content-section">
      <h2>Appetite Stimulants</h2>
      <p>When anti-nausea medication isn't enough on its own, appetite stimulants can be transformative. Both options below have legitimate evidence in cats — ask about them specifically if your cat is eating poorly.</p>

      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Mirtazapine</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Has both appetite-stimulating and anti-nausea properties. Available as a tablet or a transdermal gel applied to the ear (Mirataz) — the gel is significantly easier to administer. Typically given every 48–72 hours in cats. One of the most useful tools we had with Bruce.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Capromorelin (Elura)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">A newer liquid appetite stimulant specifically licensed for use in cats with CKD in the US. Given daily. Some cats respond better to this than mirtazapine. Ask if it's available from your vet — it became available in Canada more recently than the US.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>Ask specifically:</strong> "Should we try mirtazapine or Elura for appetite? Which would you recommend for my cat's situation?" If neither has been discussed and your cat is struggling to eat, this is a gap worth addressing.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="binders" class="content-section">
      <h2>Phosphorus Binders</h2>
      <p>When diet alone isn't keeping phosphorus in the target range, binders are added at mealtimes to bind phosphorus in the gut before it's absorbed. They need to be given with food to work.</p>

      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Aluminum hydroxide</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Highly effective and inexpensive. Available as a powder mixed into food. Long track record. Generally well tolerated, though long-term aluminum exposure is a theoretical concern — discuss with your vet.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Calcium carbonate</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Another effective binder, also inexpensive. Can raise calcium levels if used in excess — monitor calcium on bloodwork if using this option.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Epakitin / Renalzin</div>
          <div class="med-desc">A chitosan-based binder that also has some evidence for reducing BUN. Palatable powder form — easier to hide in food than some alternatives. More expensive than the above options. Epakitin is available in the US and Canada; formulations vary.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Lanthanum carbonate (Lantharenol)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">A newer option used in cats where other binders haven't achieved target phosphorus levels. Not as widely available as the above options.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="bp" class="content-section">
      <h2>Blood Pressure — The Frequently Missed One</h2>
      <p>Hypertension is extremely common in CKD cats and causes ongoing damage to the kidneys, eyes, brain, and heart — often before any outward signs appear. Despite this, blood pressure is not always checked at routine CKD appointments.</p>

      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>Ask at every CKD appointment:</strong> "Has blood pressure been measured recently?" If not, request it. Target is generally below 160 mmHg systolic.
      </div>

      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Telmisartan (Semintra)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">The first-line treatment for hypertension in cats in the US and Canada. Also reduces protein in urine, which helps slow kidney progression. Available as an oral solution — easier to dose than tablets for most cats.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Amlodipine</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Calcium channel blocker used when telmisartan isn't sufficient or tolerated. Often used in combination. Very effective at lowering blood pressure but does not have the kidney-protective protein-reducing effect of telmisartan.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="other-meds" class="content-section">
      <h2>Other Medications Worth Knowing About</h2>

      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Potassium supplementation</div>
          <div class="med-desc">CKD cats frequently develop low potassium, which causes muscle weakness and worsens kidney function. Tumil-K powder is commonly used in the US and Canada. Should be monitored with regular bloodwork — both too little and too much cause problems.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">B vitamin supplementation</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Water-soluble B vitamins are lost through excessive urination. Supplementing B12 in particular may help with appetite and energy. Often compounded or given as an injectable by the vet.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Erythropoietin (EPO) / Darbepoetin</div>
          <div class="med-desc">For CKD-related anaemia. Not a first-line treatment, but relevant for cats with significant anaemia. Requires regular monitoring. Ask your vet if anaemia is present and not improving.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="qol" class="content-section">
      <h2>Quality of Life — The Framework We Actually Use</h2>
      <p>This is the core philosophy behind this site, and it came directly from managing Minou, Bruce, and the others. CKD management can become an obsession with numbers. But your cat doesn't know their creatinine level. They know whether they feel well enough to eat, to settle in the sun, to seek you out for comfort.</p>

      <p>The signs that matter more than the bloodwork:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Is your cat eating willingly — not just accepting food, but showing interest?</li>
        <li>Are they grooming themselves, even partially?</li>
        <li>Do they seek out warmth, comfort, and company?</li>
        <li>Are they having more good days than bad?</li>
        <li>When they have a bad day, do they recover the next day?</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="content-callout">
        A cat with elevated creatinine who is eating, engaged, and seeking you out is doing better than a cat with lower numbers who hides, refuses food, and has stopped grooming. Do not let the numbers tell you the opposite of what your cat's behaviour is telling you.
      </div>

      <h3>The hardest conversation</h3>
      <p>There will come a point — as it came with Bruce, with Minou, with Yams — where the question shifts from "how do we manage this" to "are we prolonging life or prolonging suffering." That is one of the hardest questions in pet ownership, and there is no formula for it.</p>
      <p>What we can offer is this: the goal has always been a good life, not a long one. Those often overlap. When they stop overlapping, that is when the conversation changes.</p>
      <p>The <a href="{{ '/advocate/' | url }}">vet advocacy toolkit</a> has more on navigating end-of-life conversations with your vet.</p>
    </section>

